3 SENATE BILL NO. 1352 By: Stewart
4
5
6 An Act relating to medical marijuana licenses;
amending 63 O.S. 2021, Section 426.1, as last amended
7 by Section 2, Chapter 447, O.S.L. 2024 (63 O.S. Supp.
2025, Section 426.1), which relates to licensure
8 revocation hearings; excluding certain applicants
from certain provisions; updating statutory
9 reference; and providing an effective date.
10
11
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
13 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 426.1, as
14 last amended by Section 2, Chapter 447, O.S.L. 2024 (63 O.S. Supp.
15 2025, Section 426.1), is amended to read as follows:
16 Section 426.1. A. All licensure revocation hearings conducted
17 pursuant to marijuana licenses established in the Oklahoma Statutes
18 shall be recorded. A party may request a copy of the recording of
19 the proceedings. Copies shall be provided to local law enforcement
20 if the revocation was based on alleged criminal activity.
21 B. The Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority shall assist any
22 law enforcement officer in the performance of his or her duties upon
23 such request by the law enforcement officer or the request of other
24 local officials having jurisdiction. Except for license information
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1352 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 conc erning licensed patients, as defined in Section 427.2 of this
2 title, the Authority shall share information with law enforcement
3 agencies upon request without a subpoena or search warrant.
4 C. The Authority shall make available all information on
5 whether a medical marijuana patient or caregiver license is valid to
6 law enforcement electronically through an online verification
7 system.
8 D. The Authority shall make available to state agencies and
9 political subdivisions a list of marijuana-licensed premises,
10 medical marijuana businesses, or any other premises where marijuana
11 or its by-products are licensed to be cultivated, grown, processed,
12 stored, or manufactured to aid state agencies and county and
13 municipal governments in identifying locations within their
14 jurisdiction and ensuring compliance with applicable laws, rules,
15 and regulations.
16 E. 1. Any marijuana-licensed premises, medical marijuana
17 business, or any other premises where marijuana or its by-products
18 are licensed to be cultivated, grown, processed, stored, or
19 manufactured shall submit with its application or request to change
20 location, after notifying the political subdivision of its intent, a
21 certificate of occupancy from the political subdivision or State
22 Fire Marshal where the facility of the applicant or licensee is to
23 be located certifying compliance with zoning classifications,
24 applicable municipal ordinances, and all applicable safety,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1352 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 elec trical, fire, plumbing, waste, construction, and building
2 specification codes. If the political subdivision does not have an
3 authority having a jurisdiction agreement on file with the Office of
4 the State Fire Marshal, the State Fire Marshal shall certify
5 compliance with all applicable safety, electrical, fire, plumbing,
6 waste, construction, and building specification codes.
7 2. Beginning on May 28, 2021, upon the initial request for
8 renewal or transfer of a retail marijuana dispensary license, a
9 municipal government may object to the continued licensure of the
10 medical marijuana dispensary if the municipal government determines
11 it is operating contrary to the required setback distance from a
12 school including the error in measurement allowance authorized by
13 Section 425 of this title.
14 3. To prevent the granting of the grandfather provisions of
15 Section 425 of this title as a matter of law, the municipal
16 government shall provide the following documentation prior to the
17 initial renewal or transfer of a license:
18 a. a municipal resolution finding that the marijuana
19 dispensary is located within the prohibited setback
20 distance from a school that was openly in existence in
21 such a way that the public generally would have known
22 of the school’s existence and operation in that
23 location prior to the original marijuana dispensary
24 being licensed. For purposes of this subparagraph,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1352 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 “openly in existence” means any building, location, or
2 structure on a school site that has visible outward
3 markings indicating the building, location, or
4 structure was operating as a school which would serve
5 as sufficient notice of the existence of the school or
6 a reason for further inquiry on the part of the
7 marijuana dispensary license applicant. Openly in
8 existence shall not mean any school that operated
9 secretly or discreetly without any signs or other
10 markings on any building, location, or structure on
11 the school site, undeveloped land or a structure owned
12 by a school that was not openly used and marked as a
13 school site, or any school site that was established
14 after the marijuana dispensary had been established
15 and licensed by the Authority, and
16 b. documentation of the measured distance from the school
17 to the marijuana dispensary utilizing the method for
18 determining the setback distance less any allowable
19 error in measurement calculated and remeasured on and
20 after the effective date of this act May 28, 2021, as
21 authorized by Section 425 of this title.
22 4. Prior to initial renewal or transfer of a license and upon
23 receipt of documentation required by paragraph 3 of this subsection,
24 if the Authority determines that the medical marijuana dispensary is
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1352 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 oper ating contrary to the required setback distance from a school
2 including the error in measurement allowance authorized by Section
3 425 of this title, the Authority may deny the renewal or transfer of
4 the medical marijuana dispensary license and shall cause the license
5 to be revoked.
6 5. For purposes of this subsection, “school” means the same as
7 defined in Section 427.2 of this title.
8 Once a certificate of occupancy has been submitted to the
9 Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority showing full compliance as
10 outlined in this subsection, the licensee shall only need to submit
11 an affidavit for license renewal stating the premises continues to
12 comply with zoning classifications, applicable municipal ordinances,
13 and all applicable safety, electrical, fire, plumbing, waste,
14 construction, and building specification codes. An additional
15 certificate of occupancy along with an affidavit shall be submitted
16 if a change of use or occupancy occurs, or there is any change
17 concerning the facility or location that would, by law, require
18 additional inspection, licensure, or permitting by the state or
19 municipality. Municipalities or the State Fire Marshal may
20 implement an inspection program to verify compliance with this
21 subsection. The Authority shall promulgate the rules necessary for
22 the affidavit provided in this subsection. If an application for
23 renewal is submitted in violation of the provisions of this
24 subsection or information provided on the affidavit is inaccurate or
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1352 SFLR Page 5
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 untr ue, the Authority shall suspend operations of the licensee’s
2 premises until compliance is reestablished. All existing medical
3 marijuana business licensees and registrants that do not possess a
4 valid certificate of occupancy, where required, shall be subject to
5 revocation until such time as a valid certificate of occupancy is
6 obtained for all applicable structures. This provision shall not
7 apply to medical marijuana business licensees and registrants who
8 submitted a full and complete application for a valid certificate of
9 occupancy to the State Fire Marshal or political subdivision with an
10 authority having a jurisdiction agreement on file with the State
11 Fire Marshal before February 1, 2024, and while the same application
12 remains under review by the State Fire Marshal or political
13 subdivision, or in the case that the application submitted before
14 February 1, 2024, was denied, any reapplication by the same medical
15 marijuana business licensee or registrant. Medical marijuana
16 business licensees and registrants are responsible for compliance
17 with applicable state fire, building, and electrical codes and may
18 be liable for all damage that results from noncompliance with state
19 fire, building, and electrical codes to the extent authorized by
20 law.
21 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
